  "findings": [
    {
      "finding": "The conditional independence assumption S ⟂ T | (G, Z) is mathematically problematic given the definitions of S and T. Since S ∼ p(s | x, g) and T = I{G = H*(X)}, and both depend on X, S cannot be conditionally independent of T given (G, Z) unless Z contains all information about X relevant to correctness. This makes the assumption either trivially true (if Z is defined to include this information) or false for most realistic Z.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "This assumption underpins Theorem 1 (information bound), Lemma 1 (repeated self-critique bound), and much of the theoretical analysis. If the assumption doesn't hold mathematically given the variable definitions, the derivations are invalid. However, the paper acknowledges the vacuity problem, so this doesn't definitively invalidate all conclusions but requires substantial revision to clarify what the assumption actually means operationally."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The latent variable Z is not operationalized, making the central information-theoretic bound (Theorem 1) vacuous. The authors correctly note in Remark 2 that Z can always be constructed post-hoc to encode all residual dependence, making the bound I(T; S | G) ≤ I(T; Z | G) trivially satisfied. Without an a priori, independently measurable characterization of Z, the theorem has no predictive or diagnostic power.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "The paper's theoretical contribution hinges on this bound, but its vacuity undermines the framework's utility. The authors acknowledge this and shift focus to the 'falsifiable Z problem,' but this doesn't rescue the theorem as presented. The bound needs independent constraints on Z to be meaningful."
    },
    {
      "finding": "Lemma 1 (repeated self-critique bound) assumes joint conditional independence (S₁,...,Sₖ) ⟂ T | (G, Z), which is stronger than individual conditional independence. The justification that this 'holds naturally when selector evaluations are drawn independently from the same conditional distribution' is insufficient—individual conditional independence does not imply joint conditional independence without additional assumptions about the relationship between the Sᵢ given (G, Z).",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "This lemma is presented as a primary result showing that k rounds provide no more information than one. The joint independence assumption is crucial but not properly justified. If it doesn't hold, the conclusion may be incorrect. This requires clarification and potentially revision of the proof."
    },
    {
      "finding": "Theorem 2 (evidence bound) and its corollary present mathematical bounds but apply them to illustrative numerical examples (ε = 0.01, ε = 0.35) without empirical justification that these ε values correspond to real systems. The connection to empirical findings (Tsui 2025's 64.5% failure rate) is suggestive but not operational—'failure to correct' is not equivalent to Pr(A=1 | T=0).",
      "severity": "MINOR",
      "justification": "This is a minor reporting issue. The mathematical bounds are correct, but the numerical illustrations could mislead readers into thinking they represent empirical estimates. The paper appropriately cautions that these are 'mathematical illustrations,' but the presentation could be clearer about the gap between the formal quantities and measurable empirical quantities."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The paper mixes formal theoretical results with speculative mechanistic explanations (Section 3.6) and design proposals without clear demarcation. The 'predictive interpretation' based on Bender et al.'s 'stochastic parrots' framing is presented as consistent with but not dependent on the formal analysis, creating potential confusion about what is derived versus what is conjectured.",
